               <head>Glossary of the Bible</head>
					
               
               
               
               <msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85059886" rend="visible">
						
                  
                  
                  
                  <summary>A glossary of the Bible.</summary>
						
                  
                  
                  
                  <textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="yi-Hebr"/>
						
                  
                  
                  
                  <msItem rend="" class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85059886">
							
                     
                     
                     
                     <locus from="1r" to="361v"/>
							
                     
                     
                     
                     <title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Glosar le-Tana"kh</title>
							
                     
                     
                     
                     <title xml:lang="he">גלוסר לתנ"ך</title>
							
                     
                     
                     
                     <note>
								
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>The work is arranged according to the order of the biblical books, with frequent renderings in Yiddish. The books are treated in the following order: Genesis, folio 1r; Exodus, folio 16r; Leviticus, folio 27v; Numbers, folio 33v; Deuteronomy, folio 42r; Song of Songs, folio 54r; Ruth, folio 58r; Lamentations, folio 59r; Ecclesiastes, folio 63v; Esther, folio 68r; Joshua, folio 71r; Judges, folio 75v; Samuel, folio 84v; Kings, folio 102v; Jeremiah, folio 116r; Ezekiel, folio 134r; Isaiah, folio 153v; Minor Prophets, folio 194v; Psalms, folio 224r; Proverbs, folio 272r; Job, folio 288r; Daniel, folio 312r; Ezra-Nehemiah, folio 338v (incomplete); Chronicles, folio 360r (incomplete). </p>
								
                        
                        
                        
                        <p>In the prohetical books, the haftarot are indicated in the margin. The renderings of the Targum are often given.</p>
							
                     
                     
                     
                     </note>
						
                  
                  
                  
                  </msItem>
					
               
               
               
               </msContents>
					
               
               
               
